Effects of Urbanization on Barn Swallow Body Size

Winson Liu

2024-10-23

Introduction

This study investigates how urbanization affects the body size of Barn Swallows (Hirundo rustica gutturalis) in China. Data was collected from 128 sites at varying stages of urbanization, measuring physiological characteristics (body mass and wing length) of breeding individuals. The unit of observation is a singular swallow.

Methods

# Load required packages
library(tidyverse)
library(car)
library(effectsize)
library(cowplot)
library(emmeans)
library(DHARMa)  # For GLM diagnostics

# Set contrasts
options(contrasts=c("contr.poly","contr.sum"))
# Import data
BodySize_data <- read.csv("/Users/winny/Downloads/doi_10-10/Liu_Winson Dataset/Liu_Winson Dataset/BodySize_data.csv", stringsAsFactors=TRUE)

# Check for missing values
sapply(BodySize_data[c("sex", "urbanization", "body.mass", "wing.length")], 
       function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
##          sex urbanization    body.mass  wing.length 
##            0            0            0            0

Analysis 1: Sex and Urbanization Effects

Biological Question: Does urbanization affect body size differently between different sexes?

# Body mass models
mod1 = lm(body.mass ~ urbanization * sex, data=BodySize_data)
modlog1 = lm(log(body.mass) ~ urbanization*sex, data=BodySize_data)

# Wing length models
mod2 = lm(wing.length ~ urbanization * sex, data=BodySize_data)
modglm2 = glm(wing.length ~ urbanization*sex, data=BodySize_data, family="Gamma")

# Check assumptions
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(modlog1)

shapiro.test(modlog1$residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  modlog1$residuals
## W = 0.99718, p-value = 0.7962
# Results
Anova(modlog1, type=3)

# Create plots
plot1 = ggplot(data=BodySize_data, aes(x=urbanization, y=body.mass, color=sex)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=TRUE) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("red","blue")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5, face="bold")) +
  ggtitle("Sex and Urbanization on Body Mass") +
  labs(x="Urbanization (%)", y="Body Mass (g)")

plot2 = ggplot(data=BodySize_data, aes(x=urbanization, y=wing.length, color=sex)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=TRUE) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("red","blue")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5, face="bold")) +
  ggtitle("Sex and Urbanization on Wing Length") +
  labs(x="Urbanization (%)", y="Wing Length (mm)")

plot_grid(plot1, plot2, labels = "AUTO")

Analysis 2: Regional Comparison

Biological Question: Do swallows North of Beijing have larger body mass compared to swallows South of Beijing?

# Create regions and remove Beijing
BodySize_data$direction = ifelse(BodySize_data$latitude > 39.82022, "North", "South")
Swallows_direction <- filter(BodySize_data, city != "Beijing")

# Fit models
modlog3 = lm(log(body.mass) ~ direction + urbanization, data=Swallows_direction)

# Calculate means and effect sizes
emm.swallow = emmeans(modlog3, specs="direction") %>% as.data.frame()
cohen_d <- emmeans(modlog3, specs="direction") %>% 
  eff_size(sigma=sigma(modlog3), edf=df.residual(modlog3))
eta_sq <- eta_squared(modlog3, partial=FALSE)

# Results
Anova(modlog3, type=3)
## Anova Table (Type III tests)
## 
## Response: log(body.mass)
##              Sum Sq  Df    F value    Pr(>F)    
## (Intercept)  830.33   1 98351.8568 < 2.2e-16 ***
## direction      0.06   1     7.3457  0.007059 ** 
## urbanization   0.09   1    10.5566  0.001272 ** 
## Residuals      2.90 344                         
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
ggplot() +
  geom_jitter(data=Swallows_direction, 
              aes(x=direction, y=body.mass, color=direction)) +
  geom_point(data=emm.swallow, 
             aes(x=direction, y=exp(emmean)), 
             color="purple", 
             size=3) +
  geom_errorbar(data=emm.swallow, 
                aes(x=direction, 
                    ymin=exp(lower.CL), 
                    ymax=exp(upper.CL)), 
                width=0.2) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none",
        plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5, face="bold")) +
  ggtitle("Body Size in Swallows: North vs South") +
  labs(x="Direction", y="Body Mass (g)")

Results and Discussion

Analysis 1: Sex and Urbanization

  • No significant interaction between urbanization and sex (parallel regression lines)
  • Urbanization shows negative relationship with body size
  • Females have greater body mass than males
  • Males have longer wing length than females
  • Both urbanization and sex effects are significant (p<0.05)

Analysis 2: Regional Comparison

  • Statistically significant difference between regions (p<0.05)
  • Southern region shows greater average body mass
  • Small effect size (Cohens D = -0.345)
  • Eta squared = 7%, suggesting limited practical significance
  • Results contradict Bergmanns rule expectations

Limitations

  1. Statistical limitations:
    • Wing length data violated normality assumptions
    • Models didnt fully meet all assumptions
  2. Methodological limitations:
    • Simple North/South classification might oversimplify regional variation
    • Cities vary in characteristics (coastal vs.inland)
    • Potential confounding variables not included
    • Regional classification based on Beijing might not reflect true biological zones
